[{"id":27103,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["diol","monocarboxylic acid","compound with both alcohol and acid functional groups","dicarboxylic acid"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Alpha hydrogen is not present in given carbonyl compound so, Cannizzaro reaction takes place. In this reaction one molecule get oxidised to salt of carboxylic acid and another molecule get reduced to alcohol. Hydrolysis of salt of carboxylic acid will produce carboxylic acid. Reaction can be represented as below:</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/95be4e3b-5f2c-4b52-ba0d-00ebabc9eddf-bac9703c-48d7-43e3-a913-f2f5f1041d8f-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 116px;\" /></p><p>Clearly, dicarboxylic acid is not produced.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27057,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><b>DIBAL</b>-<b>H</b><b> </b>i.e., Di isobutyl aluminium hydride causes partial reduction of cyanide group along with the ester group and further hydrolysis forms corresponding aldehyde as the product. The reaction is as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOC</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mover><mo>→</mo><mrow><mtext> DIBAL- </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math></p><p>The Clemmensen reduction is a reaction that is used to reduce aldehydes or ketones to alkanes using hydrochloric acid and zinc amalgam.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>COC</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mover><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi>Zn</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&amp;</mo><mtext> conc. </mtext><mi>HCl</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math></p><p>A Grignard reagent is an organomagnesium compound which can be described by the <em>chemical formula ‘R-Mg-X’</em><em> </em>. Here aldehyde will react with Grignard's reagent to give alcohol.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi><munderover><mo>→</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>COCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOC</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mover><mo>→</mo><mrow><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOC</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math></p><p>In this reaction, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> is used as a reducing agent, to get <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOC</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math> as a product.</p><p>Hence option B is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27116,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/64004576-3c00-4779-b3b1-22d30ec64191-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f7683456-764d-44bb-a1c0-d66df6b6cc44-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/357d5893-ca55-4435-b485-9f943c51cc29-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2407a54b-185a-4f58-8449-45960750c91d-image.png\" style=\"width: 118px; height: 116px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9a3714b-425f-4e5d-9d8d-a0bde47471db-image.png\" style=\"width: 383px; height: 220px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27171,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Schiff's reagent","Tollen's reagent","$\\mathrm{I}_2$ /Alkali","Fehling's solution"],"answer":2,"solution":"Only acetaldehyde and methyl ketones give iodoform test.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27122,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Red&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></mover><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ni</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In the given reaction, only the carbonyl group has been reduced while the carbon- carbon double bonds are unaltered.</p><p>This is possible with the help of Wolf Kishner Reduction whose reagent set is given in Opiton (C).</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f6045544-a78e-4433-8fe1-cb2d0e6f4657-YUII.png\" style=\"width: 301px; height: 128px;\" /></p><p>To reduce the carbonyl groups into alkane wolf -&nbsp;kischner reduction is used, without affecting the double bond.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27101,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pt</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pd</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Na</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Sodium reacts with Hydrogen to form sodium hydride.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>NaH</mi></math></p><p>So&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Na</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;cannot be used for reduction of functional groups.</p><p>All other reagents are used as reducing agent.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27168,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Acetophenone","Iodoform","Iodoacetone","Acetic acid"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EM00259732.jpg\" style=\"width: 571px; height: 106px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27182,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/B7UuilfO7sfjir418v8uNStRyaENyUWMJ_fpfUhqQ6I.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ZxnPOOq3sH6Klq9G4UyRBjwNq3BmUrz4gykujp0kJFg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/GqEhzqaeGNSgC0Qb9fBD7XjXyrKMDZRkLsobtAagNLQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/CalwfPor8aDEGjwBhQvf-SvVGiYPRc8ICP45v1LjZqc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Aldehydic group gets oxidised to carboxylic group\nDouble bond breaks and carbon gets oxidised to carboxylic group","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":27180,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Ethyl acetate","Butan -2-one","Acetamide","Acetic acid"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27148,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/sjCPIYeCHgfFffNFxDY3e-hrlwNCHnFZPBM0bI3uRCI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gaIgVlUImpVdhaoFCWo6e2PsaALERG3ToFe5h154vSQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ZmyI4lyrU1hYuWmUZmmgVuZZUJlmVMN8o97BBOepUSM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wvICiPYs98MPLFlVBZQ__gEZ24DR9Mg5oYwXMwuywu8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/GXqAOnfdpeMbj60PZnd_PHOuZ9OPkEFSZZAPSxsctE0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27114,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>AgOH</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>AgOH</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>Ag</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Ag</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Ag</mi><msubsup><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9145a305-bb7a-431c-b6d8-f535a940ac21-image.png\" style=\"width: 440px; height: 455px;\" /></p><p>Tollens&#39; reagent is an alkaline solution of ammoniacal silver nitrate and is used to test for aldehydes. Tollens&#39; test, also known as silver-mirror test, is a qualitative laboratory test used to distinguish between an aldehyde and a ketone. It exploits the fact that aldehydes are readily oxidized (see oxidation), whereas ketones are not.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27179,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["a Schiff’s base","an enamine","an imine","an amine"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/AagGfUls6Ski_qweMXo6VmNEOVvYb-rsm41SYEaIAe8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":27121,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>CHO</mi></math>","<u><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math></u>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ba4dcfc4-49fc-4510-9aaf-305819bef057-image.png\" style=\"width: 111px; height: 53px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>OXO PROCESS (Hydroformylation) is&nbsp;&nbsp;the addition of a hydrogen atom and a formyl group to the molecule of a compound containing a double bond by reaction with hydrogen and carbon monoxide, the chief product being one or more aldehydes.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><munderover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>Rh</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>catalyst</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>CO</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e8997081-e81d-4f7b-ab65-949e7671610d-image.png\" style=\"width: 308px; height: 167px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27135,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0b4b7627-f12a-43a9-a527-3f057203e42d.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d70dd8f2-3b0f-4cf7-aac4-92279248e806.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/76e61854-d5f1-42c9-9d0b-e906bb42777e.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/35de9426-5c28-46c6-9d38-ff825799a06d.jpeg\">"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3f64e7c4-4e57-4770-83f4-03090df6b33d.jpeg\" /></p><p>Ozonolysis with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;converts alkenes into carbonyl compounds.</p><p>Alcohol upon reaction with protic acids tends to lose a molecule of water to form alkenes. These reactions are known as dehydrogenation or dehydration of alcohols. It is an example of an elimination reaction.The order of the ease of dehydration of alcohols is: tertiary &gt; secondary &gt; primary.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27124,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Copper at high temperature and pressure","Manganese acetate","Molybdenum oxide","Potassium permanganate"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Mo</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math></p><p>The reagent used will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mo</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;(molybdenum oxide) as this reagent always used to oxidise alkanes to aldehyde. So, it is widely used as&nbsp;an oxidation catalyst for acid-mediated catalytic reactions.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27080,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["(A) - III, (B) - IV, (C) - II, (D) - I","(A) - II, (B) - IV, (C) - I, (D) - III","(A) - III, (B) - IV, (C) - I, (D) - II","(A) - II, (B) - I, (C) - III, (D) - IV"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>(A) Hoffmann degradation reaction:&nbsp;Hoffmann developed a method for the preparation of primary amines by treating an amide with bromine in an aqueous or ethanolic solution of sodium hydroxide.&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8741;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>NaBr</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>(B) Clemmensen&nbsp;reduction reaction:&nbsp;The Clemmensen reduction is a reaction that is used to reduce aldehydes or ketones to alkanes using hydrochloric acid and zinc amalgam.</p><p>(C) Cannizzaro reaction:&nbsp;Aldehydes which do not have an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi></math>-hydrogen atom, undergo self-oxidation and reduction (disproportionation) reaction on heating with concentrated alkali.</p><p>(D) Reimer-Tiemann reaction:&nbsp;On treating phenol with chloroform in the presence of sodium hydroxide, a &ndash;CHO group is introduced at ortho position of benzene ring. This reaction is known as Reimer-Tiemann reaction.</p><p>So, the correct matching is given in the following table:</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 350px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\t\t\t<p>Reactions</p>\t\t\t</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Reagent used</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(A)&nbsp;Hoffmann degradation</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>NaOH</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(B) Clemmensen reduction</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(C) Cannizzaro reaction</td>\t\t\t<td>conc.KOH/ <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KOH</mi><mo>/</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(D) Reimer-Tiemann reaction</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CHCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27091,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cc40e56a-47f6-4741-91ea-47fd3afbbad3-9754878_A.png\" style=\"width: 240px; height: 39px;\" />","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c610e788-8c21-4d09-bf7f-2378bdd9e2ae-image.png\" style=\"width: 202px; height: 70px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9a484e84-cd38-47a1-b76e-d4dbace21b2a-image.png\" style=\"width: 213px; height: 70px;\" /></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>First, in this reaction the nitrile will react with the Grignard reagent. The reaction can be written as:</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/202c44d9-30aa-4776-ba10-a41440e4c4cb-e3da6922-9b97-4fc0-bb95-c9924838df77-9754878_Sol_1.png\" style=\"width: 640px; height: 150px;\" />In this step, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mg</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Br</mi></math> gets attached to the nitrogen atom and alkyl anion attacks on the electrophilic carbon of the nitrile.This step leads to the formation of&nbsp;&nbsp;imine.</p><p>Now, this reaction will further take place accordingly in the presence of aqueous acid. The reaction can be written as:</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/02cff4e4-65d9-42f9-b5bc-998ec815866d-a1b614d6-2f11-4a38-99d4-3a1292a1ef34-9754878_Sol_2.png\" style=\"width: 561px; height: 129px;\" /></p><p>Clemmenson reagent acts only on aldehydes and ketones. Therefore, butan-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-one will get reduced to butane when we treat it with zinc and hydrochloric acid.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ecd8c79e-03c6-4d71-b4ac-d79a87223f7d-9754878_Sol_3.png\" style=\"width: 570px; height: 176px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27036,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A, B and D Only","$C$ and E Only","A, C and E Only","B, C and D Only"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ltnbapzAFQG1bIvNnPBArPUUz_2KpaDUVp1mLV85o8Q.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27054,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct"],"answer":0,"solution":"Aldehyde and ketones having acidic $\\alpha$-hydrogen show aldol reaction\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/B3Z2zPLnfQsIKeiikEyZF3LRuk4mvwtYSvaaoVKm7jM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27059,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The reaction proceeds via addition of Grignard's reagent (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PhMgBr</mi></math>).</p><p>A Grignard reagent is an organomagnesium compound which can be described by the chemical formula ‘R-Mg-X’<em> </em>where R refers to an alkyl or aryl group and X refers to a halogen.</p><p>When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi>CHOOH</mi></math> reacts with grignard's reagent  benzene along with an addition product is formed, which on further reaction with aq ammonium chloride gives <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi>CHOOH</mi></math>.</p><p>Here <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math> is a strong base which is extracting proton  from the reactant to give benzene.</p><p>The reaction is as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0b000aae-f856-49e4-816b-866b12f231d7.png\" style=\"width: 752px; height: 246px;\"/></p><p>Product P is benzene and it has zero hydroxyl group.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27024,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["2-hydroxy acetophenone","4-methyl benzoic acid","4-methoxy benzaldehyde","4-hydroxy benzaldehyde"],"answer":2,"solution":"<br>(On cross aldol reaction, a single structure is obtained but it can show geometrical isomerism).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27115,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bb2d36ad-b5d4-43af-8dc4-9da12904815e-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 132px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/70ab9c0c-fded-4749-9472-b3e98a18413e-image.png\" style=\"width: 231px; height: 123px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/63dde806-0cce-40f4-abfd-359b71fe6008-image.png\" style=\"width: 202px; height: 152px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/96942885-2a64-4a4f-b73b-d1b8c36c9942-image.png\" style=\"width: 192px; height: 111px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2e700466-4a6c-4233-9ee4-ad83df42ef61-image.png\" style=\"width: 488px; height: 126px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27167,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0LH7hcXBcYP8ZNXYTdhilqtIGD3Xysy3b01XF__fJvo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/i8DNnffURIdm4B0BiR4g-61jlA3h6aazI1JxNmJTTxE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zF-2iSHq2dWY3UuYlRWDksu3WEgwzyuHE3cK2VRI248.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4qRFPAVR3wx4z0KHvVnf2oQyTvB02t-e6s28M5lr-sE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given compound $\\mathrm{A}$ is\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Ns3l7LZb9QlV9Uc_lwrcnFKEKqKxexXOagBqDBqTJb8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n$$\n\\text { Reactions given are as following : }\n$$<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0m7Jg1pFOOftdoUXYuxpAS9hoZYBobi2ilW6xqda3-U.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d1taETBtGElpAYnDsaHeHQ2LZld4fsKAN_erd0a2iN8.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zqHCX2Hvpt4cx4hWld71dTtb6pSnpdPHdHPyebRVtew.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27120,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn></math>-Dichlorobutane and Butanal","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn></math>-Dichlorobutane and Butan-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-one","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn></math>-Dichlorobutane and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Butanone","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn></math>-Dichlorobutane and Butanal"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bdea5518-99a2-4ee0-a6b0-e79fe5a18132-image.png\" style=\"width: 385px; height: 126px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Aldehydes and ketones react with hydroxyl amine to form oximes but ketones do not react with Tollens reagent.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/27a1e802-29b2-4643-8047-a274c6f92412-image.png\" style=\"width: 803px; height: 186px;\" /></p><p>Compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><none></none><mo>&#39;</mo><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mo>&#39;</mo></mmultiscripts></math> does not gives Tollen&#39;s test due to presence of kenotic group but react with hydroxyl amine</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27143,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8201;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8201;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>&nbsp;have&nbsp;active hydrogen (acidic hydrogen). So,&nbsp;acid base reaction will take place with Grignard reagent.<br /><br /><img height=\"196\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/deb77259-8b50-41c9-839d-e51ec65efbf9-image.png\" width=\"302\" /></p><p><img height=\"196\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1cac9c05-b2d4-4d38-822d-f91f140791cb-image.png\" width=\"335\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27028,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3WFQ1ErBsPwDEWMl0C15im6Uw_S1_h0EZNIf-Y2LEWk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/D2Wnvsh2y6h9yG4tOFr6I6XKaUKPKnsWWtrlZKXYf1M.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zuksUp7Vte_-IMW0pevpg0gk6Vl1PCTI8-lhqxTwTP4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/S56irARJlVPp2x5TQSqRSVveAvoS6SfeKG8kcT2QRjA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9czGwRez1i9Pk-Th7OWrNxSxdOnn3PrEghLT1Xal5SQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27027,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<br><br>","<br><br>","<br><br>","<br><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"P gives positive iodoform (has $CH_3CO-$) but negative Tollen's (no $-CHO$).<br>Q (after acid hydrolysis) gives both tests, meaning Q has both $CH_3CO-$ and $-CHO$.<br>This indicates P has an acetal protecting an aldehyde group.<br>Option (1): $CH_3-CO-CH_2-CH(OCH_3)_2$<br>Has $CH_3CO-$ → positive iodoform <br>Has acetal $-CH(OCH_3)_2$, no free aldehyde → negative Tollen's <br>Hydrolysis: $-CH(OCH_3)_2 \\xrightarrow{H^+/H_2O} -CHO$<br>Q = $CH_3-CO-CH_2-CHO$ gives both iodoform and Tollen's test <br>Molecular formula: $C_6H_{12}O_3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27118,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/39b8a788-377a-4a98-a53a-3fd94d4158cc-image.png\" style=\"width: 154px; height: 79px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1aaccd4a-9d4a-4e2f-86d0-4c101706219f-image.png\" style=\"width: 155px; height: 121px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a3d2f56a-8a77-4bee-82db-191310841f73-image.png\" style=\"width: 128px; height: 72px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fd6bc667-dcbe-4d79-bb05-97bb3f2a7cfb-image.png\" style=\"width: 156px; height: 72px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cf68d2df-a435-4106-ba73-742cac120d63-image.png\" style=\"width: 406px; height: 298px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27100,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p>(a)</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d30191fd-dd66-45ba-9d36-880827b88be6-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 103px;\" /></p><p>(b)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p>","<p>(a)</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5a74c46c-b41f-4963-8a78-c12d94e3fe2f-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 109px;\" /></p><p>(b)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PCC</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>DCM</mi></math></p>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c8de58c9-1dcd-4a9c-b9fe-86642d36894e-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 90px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bcc5a3fd-445f-42ae-8e9f-344cfc2be5dc-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 83px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Ethyl benzoate on reaction with 2 moles of grignard reagent forms a tertiary alcohol.Hence acetophenone cannot be formed in this reaction as shown below.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>COO</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi><mo>&#10230;</mo><msub><mi>PhCOCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></mrow></mover><mi>PhC</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27068,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RCHO</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi>OH</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>RCOONH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>The&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RCHO</mi></math>&nbsp;is cyclohexane carbaldehyde (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>11</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math>). The molar mass is<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>112</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math>.</p><p>The number of moles of cyclohexane carbaldehyde<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>131</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><mn>112</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>176</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;mole of aldehyde produces <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>176</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;mol aldehyde will produce</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>176</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>Mass of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> produced <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>176</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>17</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>59</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>97</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kg</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27161,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>,&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The correct order of reagents for the following reaction is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mo>]</mo><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></math>&nbsp;&amp; the reaction as well as mechanism is as follows with the correct order of reagents.</p><p>The reaction involves&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SN</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;mechanism at second step which on further reaction with excess&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></math>&nbsp;to give the final product.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e18fe0e9-d54d-4d5d-94af-83e2cfcfaa19-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 400px;\" /><br /><br />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27094,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"In an aldol condensation, an enolate ion reacts with a carbonyl compound in the presence of acid/base catalyst to form a &beta;-hydroxy aldehyde or &beta;-hydroxy ketone, followed by dehydration to give a conjugated enone. It is a useful carbon-carbon bond-forming reaction.<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b59c8e8e-e6b3-4da4-aee5-6f80f033991a-9711756_2.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 185px;\" /></p><p>As there are 2 pi bonds in the major product(P), the number of pi electrons will be equal to 4.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27076,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3ec275fc-2567-4b39-95eb-6d5541f5a3ff-9896359_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 380px; height: 130px;\" /></p><p>The above three molecules give haloform test. Acetaldehyde, methyl ketone and secondary alcohols give haloform test. In haloform test a precipitate of a methyl trihalide is formed.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27102,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Both Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> are false.","Both Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> are true.","Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> is false but Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> is true.","Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> is true but Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> is false."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d1f9e204-a0c8-46f6-a503-afaa579a8659-a24b9a0d-7eb5-4846-931d-bf892d502885-image.png\" style=\"width: 624px; height: 103px;\" /></p><p>The nucleophilic addition of hydrogen cyanide to an aldehyde or a ketone yields cyanohydrin&nbsp;as final product.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66418797-6116-4653-a4e2-cb1a0e076cbd-887bec69-9630-4be3-84fb-7d77edc5f7a6-ss.png\" style=\"width: 655px; height: 182px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27134,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a45e013e-8771-48d5-8b33-e03ea8b62c24.jpeg\" /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/71e42b20-f441-4ddd-aa3b-4c440509f6e9.jpeg\" /><br />Compound A is <img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2f01d476-4186-42f9-a983-1ca4c60cb21f.jpeg\" /><br />Percentage carbon in compound A= <math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>12</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>48</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>66.67</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]